clk: scmi: keep ACPI SCMI clocks out of disable-unused

The Sky1 ACPI CLKT lookup provider exposes firmware-managed SCMI clocks to
the common clock framework, but ACPI does not describe every CPU,
interconnect, PCIe, DDR, and boot-critical consumer.  The 6.18 ACPI clock
infrastructure therefore marked ACPI SCMI clocks CLK_IGNORE_UNUSED so the
generic late unused-clock sweep could not turn off firmware-owned resources.

Carry the same protection into the 7.0 CIX SCMI clock path.  Explicit
consumers can still prepare/enable and unprepare/disable clocks normally, but
clk_disable_unused() will leave ACPI SCMI clocks in their firmware state.

---
diff --git a/drivers/clk/clk-scmi.c b/drivers/clk/clk-scmi.c
--- a/drivers/clk/clk-scmi.c
+++ b/drivers/clk/clk-scmi.c
@@ -233,6 +233,15 @@ static int scmi_clk_ops_init(struct device *dev, struct scmi_clk *sclk,
 		.parent_data = sclk->parent_data,
 	};
 
+	if (ACPI_COMPANION(dev)) {
+		/*
+		 * ACPI firmware does not describe every consumer of SCMI clocks.
+		 * Keep them controllable by explicit users, but do not let the
+		 * unused-clock sweep turn off firmware-owned boot resources.
+		 */
+		init.flags |= CLK_IGNORE_UNUSED;
+	}
+
 	sclk->hw.init = &init;
 	ret = devm_clk_hw_register(dev, &sclk->hw);
 	if (ret)
